FL (Aug 1888), Atlanta (Nov 1888)."},{"title":"General Southern Traveling Agent","dates":"Aug 1889+","type":"railroad","notes":"'In August, 1889, he was offered and accepted the position of Gen. So. Traveling Agent, Atlanta, Ga.' (EH)"}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["railroad","georgia_migration"],"research_tags":["eh_attribution_error"],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02780","display_label":"was his father-in-law"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Georgia Railroad messenger boy risen to traveling agent","body":"When his brother-in-law Edward Werner gave Clifford his first railroad job as a messenger boy in 1874, he began a fifteen-year climb through Southern railroad management. By 1889 — two decades after his father lost everything in the Civil War — Clifford was General Southern Traveling Agent for a major rail line, based in Atlanta."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Named Atwood for his mother's Mayflower-descent family","body":"Clifford was named for his mother's family: Frances M. Atwood Cowles carried Mayflower descent ninth from Pilgrim Richard Warren (1580-1628). Clifford was a member of the Massachusetts Society of Mayflower Descendants — his 'Atwood' middle name and that membership are both direct expressions of his mother's lineage."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909, entry #1703 (Clifford Atwood Cowles)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofrev00hook","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Massachusetts Society of Mayflower Descendants — Clifford Atwood Cowles, ninth from Richard Warren","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Congressional Directory (re: father-in-law Col. Milton Anthony Candler, 44th–45th Congress 1875-1879)","accessed":"2026-05"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"clifford-cowles-1860"},"HD3781":{"id":"HD3781","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documen